,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104684"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EYou are a general practitioner seeing a 16-year-old patient who has depression. The adolescent\u0027s parent is also your patient and is aware that their child is seeing you for depression. During a separate consultation, the parent asks you for advice about how to support their child with depression and requests information about their child\u0027s condition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial response to the parent\u0027s request?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ignore the request completely to protect confidentiality","Disclose information since the parent is next of kin","Share the full treatment plan as it is in the patient\u0027s best interest","Persuade the patient to allow information sharing","Provide general information about depression without specific patient details"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate response is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eprovide general information about depression without specific patient details\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach acknowledges the parent\u0027s concerns while respecting patient confidentiality. The doctor can discuss general information about depression, available support services, and ways the parent might support their child, without breaching confidentiality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect responses are inappropriate because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShare the full treatment plan as it is in the patient\u0027s best interest\u003C/strong\u003E - This breaches patient confidentiality. Even though the patient is 16 years old, they have the right to confidentiality regarding their medical care\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisclose information since the parent is next of kin\u003C/strong\u003E - Being next of kin does not override patient confidentiality when the patient has capacity to make decisions about their healthcare\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgnore the request completely to protect confidentiality\u003C/strong\u003E - This fails to acknowledge the parent\u0027s legitimate concerns and misses an opportunity to provide helpful general information\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersuade the patient to allow information sharing\u003C/strong\u003E - While family support can be beneficial, pressuring the patient to share information disrespects their autonomy and right to confidentiality\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis situation requires balancing parental concern with the patient\u0027s right to confidentiality. While maintaining confidentiality is paramount, providing general information and support to family members is still possible and appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patient confidentiality must be maintained even when relatives request information, unless there is explicit patient consent or legal authority.","Mental health patients have the same rights to confidentiality as other patients if they have capacity to make decisions.","Doctors should acknowledge relatives\u0027 concerns while explaining professional obligations around confidentiality."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx.","Doctor\u2013patient confidentiality. In: Privacy and managing health information in general practice, RACGP [online]. 2023; cited 2025 Jan 18. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/running-a-practice/security/managing-practice-information/privacy-of-health-information/privacy-law/doctor-patient-confidentiality-7"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87038"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18920"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87038"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-03T20:10:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-03T20:10:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11653"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104684"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt